snippet.textDisplay: @oskar recon Vaccines trigger the body's immune system to produce antibodies to a specific disease. The triggering mechanism can be anything from a similar virus (the use of relatively harmless cowpox virus to immunize against smallpox back in the 1790s), to a weakened form of the actual disease virus (early polio vaccines) to fragments of the virus that will trigger an immune response without causing the disease. Polio was eradicated by a massive inoculation campaign once the vaccine was developed. Clinical trials were started in 1954 just as a new polio epidemic was starting. In 1955 there were nearly 60,000 new polio cases just as the massive worldwide polio vaccination started. By 1957, there were only 6,000 new cases of polio in the US. Polio was eradicated in the developed world by the 1970s and exists today in only a few parts of Africa and Asia.
